Epoch:1 | IDEA | Scientist1:Thought: Current approaches to integrating knowledge graphs (KGs) into generative commonsense reasoning either treat KGs as static retrieval modules (limiting coverage and adaptability) or train models directly on symbolic KG triples, which restricts natural language fluency and contextual sensitivity. While methods like COMET demonstrate that pre-trained language models (PLMs) can generate plausible commonsense inferences, they often rely on fixed pre-training objectives that do not dynamically adapt to structural knowledge during training. Furthermore, most existing strategies fail to generalize compositionally to unseen concept combinations—a critical requirement for robust AI reasoning. My key insight is that instead of treating KG structure as either external or symbolic, we should *learn to instantiate latent graph structures during pre-training*, allowing the model to dynamically construct and refine relational reasoning pathways conditioned on linguistic context. This would enable adaptive knowledge integration without requiring explicit symbolic alignment at inference time. Unlike CoSe-Co, which conditions generation on input text using a fixed KG-derived dataset, or prefix-tuning methods that only modify attention prefixes, my approach embeds *graph-structural priors directly into the pre-training phase* via latent variable modeling. The proposed method introduces a dual-path architecture where one stream learns semantic representations while the other induces soft, differentiable graph topologies over latent concepts—enabling generalization to novel compositions by recombining learned relational patterns. This differs fundamentally from prior work by making KG structure an emergent, trainable component of the model rather than a fixed input or post-hoc retrieval system.

